## Part 1: What Is a Large Language Model, Really?

At the most basic level, every one of these three products — ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini — is built on the same foundational architecture you already learned about on Day 6: the **Transformer**. Specifically, they are all "decoder-style" or "decoder-heavy" transformer models trained to do one core task extremely well: **predict the next token (word-piece) in a sequence, given everything that came before it.**

That's it. That's the entire mathematical objective at the core. Everything that feels like "intelligence" — answering questions, writing code, reasoning through a math problem, holding a conversation — emerges from a model that has gotten extremely good at the deceptively simple task of "what word comes next."

### Why does predicting the next word produce something that looks like intelligence?

Because to predict the next word *well*, across trillions of words of text covering science, code, conversation, literature, arguments, tutorials, and more, the model is forced to build internal representations of grammar, facts, relationships between concepts, reasoning patterns, and even style. If you're trying to predict the next token in "The mitochondria is the ___ of the cell," you need to have absorbed biology facts to get "powerhouse" right most of the time. If you're predicting the next line of Python after a `for` loop, you need to have absorbed programming syntax and logic. Scale this prediction task up across essentially all of humanity's digitized text, run it through a network with billions of parameters, and the emergent behavior looks like broad, general competence — even though the underlying training signal was always just "predict the next token."

### Tokens — the actual unit of "thought"

None of these models see words the way you do. Before any text reaches the model, it gets broken into **tokens** — small chunks that might be a whole word, part of a word, or a punctuation mark. "Understanding" might become one token, while "internationalization" might get split into "international" + "ization." Every one of your prompts gets converted into a sequence of token IDs (numbers), and every response is generated **one token at a time**, feeding each newly generated token back into the model to predict the next one. This is why long responses take visibly longer to generate than short ones — the model is doing a full forward pass through its billions of parameters for every single token.

### The Transformer's "attention" mechanism

The key architectural innovation (from Day 6) is **self-attention**. As the model generates each token, it doesn't just look at the immediately preceding word — it computes a weighted relationship between the token it's about to generate and every other token in the conversation so far. This lets it "attend to" a name mentioned 2,000 words ago, or connect a pronoun back to the noun it refers to, or recognize that a coding question relates to an error message pasted much earlier. Modern context windows (how much text a model can "see" at once) range from tens of thousands to over a million tokens depending on the model, and attention is what makes using all of that context possible — though attending to very distant, sparse details is still harder for a model than attending to nearby context, which is part of why "needle in a haystack" performance varies across models.

